1.c: None.
1.b: All city facilities, schools, churches and good transportation.
1.a: Fairly high ground, rising from the north.

2.a: Mixed white collar and Skilled labor

areaDesc.5: This area is predominantly two family (six room flats) which have practically no market at present. About twenty years ago, some ten or fifteen houses costing around $35,000. a piece were built- entirely out of keeping with the neighborhood.

1.c: None.
1.b: All city facilities, except sewers. Area restricyed to one family homes. Very low taxes adn good transportation, schools, etc.

areaDesc.5: This is a new development just over the city line having the advantages of easy accessibility and very low taxes.

6.1: Benton Hills- Town of New Hartford

1.c: Adjacence of poorer and industrial districts.
1.b: All city facilities, good transportation, schools, etc.
1.a: Land rises slightly from low ground in the north.

areaDesc.5: Attractive to members of Blessed Sacrament congregation.

6.1: Yorkville Village & Utica Blessed Sacrament District

1.c: Poor accessibility. Railroad with some industry. Construction is poor.
1.b: All city facilities.

areaDesc.5: Portion northwest of the railroad is Italian and that southest is Polish. This area has been slightly improved by paved sidewalks, streets and street lighting.

1.c: Age and obsolescence of structures.
1.b: All city facilities and convenience to center of city.
1.a: Land rises from low in the north.

areaDesc.5: York Heights section is somewhat better than the rest of the area. It is a fairly good district for modest quarters and largely limited to those of Polish descent.

1.c: Age and obsolescence as well as industry and business.
1.b: All city facilities adn adjacence to business center.
1.a: Terrain is low and rises slightly to the south.

areaDesc.5: All of Utica's small Negro population is concentrated in this area along the railroad tracks. Many of the old, single houses have been converted into two family.

1.c: Age and obsolescence, type of structures and population as well as distance from the center of Utica.
1.b: All city facilities.
1.a: Low land rising to the south.

1.c: Age and obsolescence of structures as well as adjacence to railroad and industry.
1.b: All city facilities, good transportation, schools, etc.

1.c: Age and obsolescence of dwellings, infiltration of business and less desirable inhibitants.
1.b: All city facilities and adjacent to center of city.
1.a: Land is low, rising slightly to south.

2.a: Mixed White collar, skilled labor, etc.

areaDesc.5: This is a very old residential area with some modern apartments. There are also some very old and very large private residences with present purely nominal values for conversion purposes.

1.c: Age and obsolescence of structure, encroachment of business and infiltration of less desirable inhabitants.
1.b: All city facilities and adjacence to center of city.
1.a: Land is low, rising to south.

2.a: Mixed White collar, skilled labor, etc.

areaDesc.5: A number of singles have been converted into two family houses. This area was originally built up as one of the city's desirable neighborhoods but has been declining for many years. Conversion to multiples, rooming houses and business is in process. Likewise, the Italian district in area "D-2" is steadily expanding to this section.

1.c: Age and obsolescence of structures, and distance from center of Utica.
1.b: All city facilities. New School.
1.a: Low land, rising to the south.

2.a: Low Income White collar, skilled labor, etc.

areaDesc.5: This is a very old village- older than Utica- which has witnessed a small amount of building in recent years. This is partly due to its proximity to the textile mills. West Whitesboro Road has recently been extended through the Village as an express highway.

1.c: Age and obsolescence and poor type structures.
1.b: All city facilities.

areaDesc.5: This is a very old village which is mainly inhabited by workers in the Julliard Textile Mills. This Mill owns a number of the houses accommodating these workers.

1.c: Types of structures and inhabitants.
1.b: All city facilities, fair transportation, good schoools and churches

areaDesc.5: This is a modest area including many two family (six room flats), a large portion of which are in very poor repair. It has been an overflow district from "D-2".

1.c: Somewhat limited to persons of Italian descent. These are of good class, but races are not inclined to mix in this city.
1.b: All city facilities and accessibility to schools, etc. Transportation is good. Zone A (one & two family homes).

1.c: Transportation only fair. Poor type of structures and inhabitants.
1.b: All city facilities as well as accessibility to schools and churches.

areaDesc.5: Sparsely settled area; much of which is given over to truck gardens with small shacks.

1.b: Undeveloped.
1.a: Land is level and fairly high.

areaDesc.5: In addition to a very few scattered dwellings which, in the main, are very small or shacks in connection with truck gardens, this area contains at present a large modern school and an armory. On the Parkway, near Armory Drive, is to be built a large low rent housing project and this may affect the calibre of future development unfavorably.

1.c: Transportation is not good in outlying sections.
1.b: All city facilities as well as low taxes. Village zoning restrictions are very rigid.

areaDesc.5: This is a very old village which is very highly regarded because of its attractive topography, low taxes and adjacence to the southern boundary of Utica. Oxford Road consists almost entirely of very old houses in large grounds, many of which are used to accommodate tourists. Piffin Hill has modern homes in large grounds. Oxford Heights is likewise a modern development of good calibre.

6.1: Village of New Hartford Piffing Hill- Oxford Hgts.

1.c: Located on the wrong side of town. Unpleasant odors from industry.
1.b: All city facilities. New school.

2.a: Mixed white collar and skilled labor

areaDesc.5: Small attempts to develop this side of town have been mostly unsuccessful. The trend of growth has been all to the south. Likewise, in order to reach this section, it is necessary to cross a wide stretch of industrial territory. There are some odors from a gas plant.

1.c: None.
1.b: All city facilities, good transportation, schools, etc. Zone A (one and two family homes).

areaDesc.5: This is a convenient area of good medium type located in the most desirable end of town. It will be noted that two family dwellings are very unpopular. Houses are built only on the lower side of the Parkway (Pleasant Street) and have unobstructed outlook over large park area.

1.c: Largely cheap construction.
1.b: All city facilities, fair transportation adn sufficiency of schools and churches.

areaDesc.5: Many of the houses on the streets between Roosevelt Drive and Sunset can be classed as "Jerry" built and are in poor condition although of fairly recent construction.

6.1: South Utica Roosevelt Drive- French Road

1.c: Distance from neighborhood stores.
1.b: All city facilities, low taxes and very attractive topography. Schools, churches, etc. are reasonably accessible. Area is highly restricted to one family.
1.a: Ground is high and rolling. Hillside.

areaDesc.5: This is a very desirable section for larger scale homes with large plots. Original cost of houses runs as high as $150,000.

6.1: Sherman Hills- Town of New Hartford

1.c: High taxes and no convenient neighborhood shopping center. Multiple low cost housing projects threatening future of this area.
1.b: All city facilities. Area restricted to one family homes. Schools, churches, etc.

areaDesc.5: Regarded as the choicest residential area within the city limits. Some of the houses cost far more than the top figured of $40,000. given above. The housing project mentioned is not near enough to affect the present development of this section but may limit, to some degree, its future expansion.

1.c: Age and obsolescence of structures as well as mixture of business and industry.
1.b: All city facilities and adjacence to center of city.
1.a: Ground is low, rising slightly to the south.

areaDesc.5: The main concentration of Utica's large population (estimated at about thirty-five thousand) of Italians and those of Italian descent. About 70% of the inhabitants of this area are of this description. Many old single houses have been converted into two family. Also, some residential structures have been converted into combination store and dwelling. A few multiple structures containing three or more units are in this area.

1.c: None, except high tax burden.
1.b: All city facilities. Area is restricted to one-family homes. Some portions are also restricted as to price and design. Excellent transportation, schools, etc.

areaDesc.5: Most of Utica's growth of good grade intermediate priced houses, over the past 15 years, has occured in this section. There are not over half a dozen two family houses on the edges of thsi area which are comparable to the better ones in other sections of the city.

6.1: Proctor Boulevard- Blaikie Terrace Ridgewood- Fairview Heights sub-divisions

1.c: High taxes. Higher ground surrounding this area is considered as more desirable.
1.b: All city facilities and restricted to one family homes.
1.a: This section is comparatively low-lying; being situated in a valley.

areaDesc.5: The small area west of Genesee Street is somewhat higher grade and might deserve and "A" rating.
